What does `builder.toString()` return? Let me check.

OK, but regardless, for `startRev=1,endRev=1`, the `superChangeset` is null and the deletion branch is skipped. So maybe the reported `createDiffHTML(1,1)` failure is actually from a different issue.

BUT - actually, let me look at the `builder.toString()` output. If the text is empty (new pad with no content), it might produce an empty changeset string or something unexpected.

Let me focus on what I know is a definite bug: the prototype override of `_createDeletionChangeset` with an empty function body. This will cause any call with `startRev != endRev` to fail.

Now let me understand the fix. The simplest fix is to remove lines 461-466 (the prototype override). But I should first understand why this override exists. Let me look at git blame if possible.

Since there's only one commit, let me look at the original source to understand if this might be a TypeScript compilation artifact or an intentional stub:

The comment says "this method is 80% like Changeset.inverse." This suggests this was being reworked but the old method body was moved to prototype and left empty, while the new method body was put in the class. It seems like a mistake where someone started refactoring but left the old override in place.

Let me verify by looking at what the class `_createDeletionChangeset` implementation does:

The class method at line 242 defines the full implementation. The prototype override at line 464 is an empty function. The prototype override takes precedence because in JavaScript, when you override `PadDiff.prototype._createDeletionChangeset` after the class is defined, all instances will use the prototype version instead of the class version.

Wait, actually that's not how ES6 classes work in JavaScript. Let me think about this...

Actually, in JavaScript, class methods ARE on the prototype. So when you do:
```javascript
class PadDiff {
  _createDeletionChangeset(cs, startAText, apool) {
    // full implementation
  }
}

// This OVERRIDES the class method on the prototype
PadDiff.prototype._createDeletionChangeset = function(cs, startAText, apool) {
  // empty!
};
```

The second assignment replaces the method on the prototype. Since instances look up methods on the prototype chain, all instances will use the empty function. This is the bug.

The fix is to remove lines 461-466 of padDiff.ts.

